OSI MODEL (Open Systems Interconnection Model)
A conceptual framework developed by the International Organization for Standardization to standardize how different systems communicate over a network.
It divides communication into 7 layers, each with specific responsibilities.

1. Physical Layer (Layer 1)

Function: Transmits raw bits over a physical medium.
Key Responsibilities:
Electrical/optical signal transmission
Bit synchronization
Data rate control
Physical topology (bus, star, ring)
Examples: Cables, hubs, repeaters, network interface hardware
Data Unit: Bits

2. Data Link Layer (Layer 2)

Function: Provides node-to-node data transfer and error detection.
Key Responsibilities:
Framing (packaging bits into frames)
MAC addressing
Error detection and correction
Flow control
Sub-layers:
LLC (Logical Link Control)
MAC (Media Access Control)
Examples: Switches, Ethernet protocols
Data Unit: Frames

3. Network Layer (Layer 3)

Function: Determines how data is routed between devices across networks.
Key Responsibilities:
Logical addressing (IP addresses)
Path determination (routing)
Packet forwarding
Fragmentation and reassembly
Examples: Routers, IP protocol
Data Unit: Packets

4. Transport Layer (Layer 4)

Function: Ensures reliable data delivery between end systems.
Key Responsibilities:
End-to-end communication
Error recovery and retransmission
Flow control
Segmentation and reassembly
Protocols: TCP (reliable), UDP (unreliable)
Data Unit: Segments

5. Session Layer (Layer 5)

Function: Manages sessions (connections) between applications.
Key Responsibilities:
Session establishment, maintenance, termination
Synchronization checkpoints
Dialog control (full/half duplex)
Data Unit: Data

6. Presentation Layer (Layer 6)

Function: Translates data formats between application and network.
Key Responsibilities:
Data encoding/decoding
Encryption/decryption
Compression/decompression
Examples: SSL/TLS formatting, data conversion (ASCII, JPEG, etc.)
Data Unit: Data

7. Application Layer (Layer 7)

Function: Provides network services directly to user applications.
Key Responsibilities:
Interface for end-user processes
File transfer, email, web services
Examples: HTTP, FTP, SMTP, DNS
Data Unit: Data
